  "prompt": "What is the difference between a Banker's Cheque and Normal Cheque?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between a Banker's Cheque and a Normal Cheque:\n\nBanker's Cheque:\n1. Issued by bank on its own account\n2. Guaranteed payment by the bank\n3. Funds are already set aside\n4. Cannot be dishonored\n5. Considered more secure\n6. Higher degree of credibility\n7. Usually involves a fee for issuance\n8. Typically used for large transactions\n9. Has more legal validity\n10. Requires bank account to be pre-funded\n\nNormal Cheque:\n1. Issued by an individual from their bank account\n2. Payment depends on account balance\n3. Can be dishonored if insufficient funds\n4. Less secure\n5. Lower credibility\n6. No additional charge for writing\n7. Used for regular transactions\n8. Less legal standing\n9. Depends on account holder's creditworthiness\n10. Drawn against existing account balance\n\nBoth are negotiable instruments, but a Banker's Cheque provides more payment assurance compared to a normal cheque.",
